of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\n\n[defendant] DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\n# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\n# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\n# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\n# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\n# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.13