dow.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\\n# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that