s a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\n# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but